{
  "doc_id": "54591",
  "text": "With respect to mechanisms of action of IVIG, Sewell and Jolles (1) [CITATION_1] . Recently, the CD200 tolerance signal has been shown to be important for suppression of NK activity (as shown in Fig. 2 ) by IVIG [CITATION_2] ; interestingly, the CD56 bright subset of NK cells and NKT cells, which have been viewed as of particular importance at the feto-maternal interface express receptors for CD200 [CITATION_3] . CD200 may be particularly important as the CD200 molecule binds to CD200R2/3 on antigen-presenting cells, which then activate CD4 + 25 + Treg cells [CITATION_4] ; these Treg cells prevent autoimmune disease, and also prevent spontaneous abortion and infertility in mice [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . These data suggest that additional measurements of CD200-dependent IVIG effects should be made in patients in RCTs to determine if the treatment is working. Current controversy would not likely survive the impact of such data.",
